  "prompt": "What causes a sonic boom?",
  "response": "A sonic boom is caused by an object traveling faster than the speed of sound, which is approximately 767 mph (1,235 km/h) at sea level. When an aircraft or other object moves through the air, it creates pressure waves in front of and behind it. \n\nWhen the aircraft is traveling at subsonic speeds (slower than the speed of sound), these pressure waves can move out of the way in all directions, spreading out and becoming weaker over distance. However, when the aircraft exceeds the speed of sound, it moves faster than the pressure waves can move out of its way. As a result, the waves are compressed and form a single shock wave, which trails behind the aircraft in a cone shape.\n\nWhen this shock wave passes over an observer on the ground, it creates a sudden change in pressure, resulting in the characteristic \"boom\" sound. The sonic boom is often heard as a double boom, due to the two shock waves (one at the nose and one at the tail of the aircraft) that are produced by the aircraft. \n\nThe intensity of the sonic boom depends on factors such as the size and shape of the aircraft, its speed and altitude, and the atmospheric conditions.",
